<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-262-084  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 262 084.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  March 6 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>U.S. export controls to Eastern Europe easing.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>McMullen, Barbara E.; McMullen, John F.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer industryGovernment RegulationLegal IssuesExportEastern Europe.andO;Person:    Mosbacher, Robert A. (attitudes).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>U.S.andP;  EXPORT CONTROLS TO EASTERN EUROPE EASING WASHINGTON, D.C., U.S.A, 1990MAR 1 (NB) -- Testifying before the House Ways and Means Committee, CommerceSecretary Robert &quot;Buz&quot; Mosbacher said that progress was being made to allowmore exports of computers to Eastern European countries.andM;Mosbacher said the United States feels that it would be easier to shipcomputers and other high-tech items to Poland, Hungry and Czechoslovakia thanto the Soviet Union which still represents a military threat.andM;Representative William Frenzel (Republican.andP;  - Mich) stated that the existinglaw, Export Administration Act, makes it difficult for American firms to dobusiness in Europe.andP;  This law, administrated by the Commerce Department,restricts shipments of high technology goods, including computers, tocommunist countries if the goods have potential military application.andM;Historically, the limits imposed under the Act have been a source of debatewithin the government between the Commerce and Defense Departments, with theDefense Department generally pushing for more stringent controls while theCommerce Department favoring more liberal interpretation of the regulations.andM;Mosbacher was quoted as saying, &quot;I think we can reach agreements on contractsshortly to raise the technology that we ship to Eastern Europe to a higherlevel even than to the U.S.S.R.&quot; He explained that Poland and Hungry, inexchange for receiving high- tech exports, have agreed to let the UnitedStates verify that the exports are not being used for military purposes ortransshipped to a third country and that Czechoslovakia has offered to do thesame.andP;  He also noted that the United States has proposed liberalization ofrules governing three areas, telecommunications, machine tools and computers,to its partners on the Coordinating Committee for Multilateral ExportControls.andM;(Barbara E. McMullen andamp; John F. McMullen/19900303)</TEXT></DOC>